         WHO makes a pandemic agreement
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/multisectoral-national-plans-human-animal-environment-disease-drivers.png" alt="States must develop multisectoral national plans, including measures to identify and address the drivers of disease at the human-animal-environment interface" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>States must develop multisectoral national plans, including measures to identify and address the drivers of disease at the human-animal-environment interface. Credits: AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      The World Health Organization (WHO) adopted the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-pandemic-agreement?source=website" target="_blank">Pandemic Agreement</a> at the 78th World Health Assembly in Geneva. This agreement, which took over three years of negotiations, aims to improve global preparedness and coordinate responses to future pandemics. The agreement <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-strives-to-prevent?source=website" target="_blank">strives to prevent</a> the fragmented global response by enhancing global surveillance, information sharing, and equal permission to vaccines and treatments.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        A key part of the agreement, the Pathogen Access and Benefit-Sharing (PABS) mechanism, is still in the works. It will detail how countries share virus samples and the resulting health benefits. Director General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus praised the accord as a major milestone, calling it “a victory for public health, science, and multilateral measures.” </p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
       Countries have until May 2026 to amend the accord. After that, at least 60 nations must ratify it for it to take effect. The negotiations faced tensions between wealthy and developing nations, especially on vaccine availability. Critics voiced concerns about national sovereignty, but negotiators stressed that the pact respects countries' independence while ensuring global safety. </p>
       
        </mj-text>
